rn, cantigas de escárnio are satiric, and sometimes outrageously obscene, lyrics whose targets include aristocrats, corrupt clergy, promiscuous women, and homosexuals.Complete with an illuminating introduction on the history of the cantigas, their poetic characteristics, and the men who composed and performed them, this engaging volume is filled with exuberant and unexpected poems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPortuguese poetryyTo 1500vTranslations into English. 0aSongs, PortuguesevTexts. 0aTroubadour songsvTexts. 7aPOETRY / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aAdjective.  aAiras Nunes.  aAlbigensian Crusade.  aAlfonso X of Castile.  aAnother Girl.  aArabic.  aAristocracy.  aAwareness.  aBertran de Born.  aCantiga de amigo.  aCantiga.  aCantigas de Santa Maria.  aCantigas.  aCastile (historical region).  aCastilian Spanish.  aCatharism.  aConvulsion.  aCopyist.  aCount of Barcelos.  aCritical edition (opera).  aEdition (book).  aEmotion.  aErysipelas.  aEzra Pound.  aFee tail.  aFeeling.  aFerdinand III of Castile.  aFrom a Distance.  aFrustration.  aFungus.  aGalicia (Eastern Europe).  aGalicia (Spain).  aGalician language.  aGalician-Portuguese.  aGalicians.  aGautier de Coincy.  aGenre.  aGlossary.  aHoly Roman Emperor.  aImpossibility.  aIn Battle.  aIndividualism.  aInternal rhyme.  aKharja.  aKingdom of Galicia.  aLament.  aLeitmotif.  aLiterature.  aLyric poetry.  aLyricist.  aMajorat.  aMarcabru.  aMelodic (magazine).  aMendes.  aModern English.  aMoors.  aMusic Is.  aMusical notation.  aMy Way.  aNarrative.  aNobility.  aObscenity.  aOccitan language.  aOccitania.  aOccitans.  aOn the Third Day.  aPanegyric.  aPeire Vidal.  aPerfect rhyme.  aPhilip Glass